05056nam a22006855i 9780824841317DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20042004hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248413177 a10.1515/97808248413172doi  a(DE-B1597)484658  a(OCoLC)1041994082  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aSOC0320002bisacsh1 aBao, Jiemin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aMarital Acts :bGender, Sexuality, and Identity among the Chinese Thai Diaspora /cJiemin Bao. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2004] 4c©2004  a1 online resource (248 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tLanguage Conventions -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tPart I Positions -- t1. Introduction -- t2. The Ongoing Process of Identity Formation -- tPart II The Chinkao Experience -- t3. The Gendered Politics of Migration and Marriage -- t4. Middle-Class Chinese-ness, Nei/Wai Politics -- t5. Changes in Sexual Practice: “Same Bed, Different Dreams” -- tPart III The Lukchin Experience -- t6. Hybrid Identities -- t7. What’s in a Wedding? -- t8. Naturalized Sexuality and Middle-Class Respectability -- t9. Shang Jia: “Family Business” -- tPart IV The Chinese Thai American Experience -- t10. Multiple Belongings -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSucceeding waves of migration, from China to Thailand and from Thailand to the United States, have helped shape the identities of three generations of diasporic Chinese Thai. In this exciting new study, Jiemin Bao focuses on how cultural identities--as seen through the lens of marriage--play a central role in the formation of cultural citizenship. By challenging models of cultural identity that separate gender, sexuality, and class into discrete domains of analysis, Bao examines the competing roles of sex/gender, class, and race/ethnicity in shaping the ongoing construction of Chinese Thai identities in contemporary Bangkok and the San Francisco Bay area. Marriage has long been treated as a mechanism of assimilation in the anthropological literature on diasporic Chinese: the Chinese "minority" is absorbed into the dominant "majority" through intermarriage. Bao approaches marriage differently, viewing it not only as an institution that fosters and reproduces fundamental ideas of masculinity and femininity, but also as a site where the various categories of ethnicity, class, gender, and sexuality--the stuff of identity--intersect. Through a fine-grained analysis of the lives of men and women and the language that three generations use to talk about their experiences in different locales, Bao powerfully demonstrates how masculine and feminine identities are both classed and ethnicized in Thailand and the United States. Nuanced and provocative, Marital Acts shows how diasporic Chinese are both self making and being made, not once, but twice--first in the society in which they are born and second in the society to which they migrate.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gender Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUHP eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Hawaii Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066325940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082484131740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824841317423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780824841317/original  a978-3-11-056414-3  UHP eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-064977-2  Asian Studies Backlist